The paper discusses the development and interpretation of similarity models, which are commonly used in machine learning algorithms such as kernel machines, nearest neighbors, clustering, or anomaly detection. These algorithms are typically used in computer vision (cs.CV), natural language processing (cs.CL), information retrieval (cs.IR), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) applications. The paper specifically focuses on deep similarity models, which are a subset of machine learning models that use deep neural networks. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the most likely sub-category, followed by cs.CV, cs.CL, cs.IR, and cs.AI.
